public class EdiTraining : TrainingContentBase
{
    public EdiTraining(AppDbContext db, Dictionary<string, int> slugMap) : base(db, slugMap) { }

    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "EDI Overview",
            Slug = "edi-overview",
            Summary = "What EDI is, the X12 and EDIFACT formats, how trading partners, transactions, and mappings work together in QB Engineer.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","admin","integrations"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## EDI Overview\n\nElectronic Data Interchange (EDI) lets your shop exchange structured business documents — purchase orders, invoices, shipping notices, and more — with trading partners electronically instead of through paper, email, or manual data entry.\n\nQB Engineer's EDI module lives under Admin > EDI and gives you a central place to manage trading partners, monitor inbound and outbound transactions, configure field mappings, and handle errors with retry support.\n\n### What Is EDI?\n\nEDI replaces manual document exchange with standardized electronic formats. When a customer sends you a purchase order via EDI, it arrives as a structured data file that QB Engineer can parse, validate, and automatically apply — creating a Sales Order, Purchase Order, or other entity without anyone retyping the information.\n\nThe reverse also works: when you ship an order, QB Engineer can generate an outbound EDI document (like an ASN or invoice) and send it to the trading partner automatically.\n\n### EDI Formats\n\nQB Engineer supports two major EDI standards:\n\n- **X12** — The dominant standard in North America. Transaction sets are identified by three-digit numbers: 850 (Purchase Order), 810 (Invoice), 856 (Advance Ship Notice), 855 (PO Acknowledgment), and many more.\n- **EDIFACT** — The international standard used widely outside the US. Uses alphabetic message type codes like ORDERS, INVOIC, DESADV.\n\nEach trading partner is configured with a default format, but individual transactions can use either format.\n\n### Trading Partners\n\nA trading partner is any company you exchange EDI documents with — typically customers or vendors. Each partner record stores:\n\n- **EDI identifiers** — Qualifier ID and Qualifier Value that uniquely identify the partner in EDI envelopes. The Interchange Sender/Receiver IDs and Application Sender/Receiver IDs route documents correctly.\n- **Format and transport** — Whether the partner uses X12 or EDIFACT, and how documents are delivered (AS2, SFTP, VAN, Email, API, or Manual).\n- **Processing rules** — Whether inbound documents are auto-processed or held for manual review, and whether the partner requires functional acknowledgments (997/CONTRL).\n- **Links** — A partner can be linked to an existing Customer or Vendor record in QB Engineer for automatic entity matching.\n\n### Transactions\n\nEvery EDI document exchange creates a transaction record. Transactions track:\n\n- **Direction** — Inbound (received from partner) or Outbound (sent to partner).\n- **Transaction Set** — The document type (e.g., 850 for a Purchase Order, 810 for an Invoice).\n- **Control Numbers** — Interchange, Group, and Transaction control numbers that uniquely identify the document in the EDI envelope.\n- **Status lifecycle** — Each transaction moves through a processing pipeline: Received → Parsing → Parsed → Validating → Validated → Processing → Applied (success) or Error/Rejected (failure).\n- **Related entity** — Once processed, the transaction links to the QB Engineer entity it created or updated (e.g., a Sales Order, PO, or Invoice).\n- **Error handling** — Failed transactions show the error message and can be retried. The retry count and last retry timestamp are tracked.\n- **Acknowledgments** — When a partner requires acknowledgments, the system tracks whether the 997/CONTRL was sent and links the acknowledgment transaction.\n\n### Part-Number Translation (the Part-Number Map)\n\nTrading partners almost never order using *your* part numbers — they use their own. EDI translation bridges that gap. Each trading partner has a **Part-Number Map**: a simple two-column table that says \"when this partner says part X, they mean our part Y.\"\n\nYou open the map from the partner row's **⇄ (swap) action** on the Trading Partners tab. The map is a typed grid — one row per pair of (Partner Part #, Our Part #) — not a code or JSON editor. As you type your part number, the map resolves it against the live part catalog and shows the matched part's description; a part number that matches nothing in the catalog is flagged so you can see the data-quality gap before an order arrives.\n\nYou can build the map two ways:\n\n- **Add rows by hand** — for a handful of parts, click Add Row and type each pair.\n- **Import a CSV** — for a long cross-reference, import a two-column CSV (Partner Part #, Our Part #). The import upserts by partner number, so re-importing an updated file refreshes existing rows instead of duplicating them.\n\nThe map is per-partner because every customer numbers parts differently.\n\n### How an Inbound 850 Translates (mental model)\n\nWhen a customer sends an EDI Purchase Order (transaction set **850**), each order line carries *the partner's* part number. QB Engineer translates each line before it becomes a Sales Order:\n\n1. The line's partner part number is looked up in **that partner's Part-Number Map**.\n2. If the map has a match, the line is matched to your catalog part and the Sales Order line is created against your part.\n3. If the line is unmapped — or it maps to a part number that doesn't exist in your catalog yet — the line is **still created**, but it keeps the partner's number in the order-line notes so someone can complete the match by hand.\n\nThis is intentionally a *number swap* — the 90% case. Unit-of-measure and pack-quantity translation are documented extensions, not built today. The takeaway: keep each partner's Part-Number Map current and you eliminate the manual matching step on every inbound order.\n\n### Transport Methods\n\nQB Engineer supports multiple ways to send and receive EDI documents:\n\n- **AS2** — The most common B2B protocol. Encrypted, signed, with built-in receipt (MDN) support.\n- **SFTP** — Secure file transfer. Documents are placed in partner-specific directories.\n- **VAN** — Value Added Network. A third-party service that routes documents between partners (e.g., SPS Commerce, TrueCommerce).\n- **Email** — EDI documents sent as email attachments. Simple but less automated.\n- **API** — Direct REST/SOAP API integration with the partner's system.\n- **Manual** — Documents are uploaded/downloaded manually through the QB Engineer UI. Good for low-volume partners or testing.\n\n### Inbound Polling and Auto-Processing\n\nWhen Auto Process is enabled on a trading partner, QB Engineer automatically processes inbound documents through the full pipeline — parsing the EDI content, validating against the mapping rules, and applying the data to create or update entities. When Auto Process is off, inbound documents stop at the Received status for manual review before processing.\n\n### When to Use EDI\n\n- When a customer or vendor requires electronic document exchange\n- When you want to eliminate manual data entry for recurring orders\n- When you need an auditable trail of every document exchanged with a partner\n- When your trading partner uses a VAN or AS2 and expects automated acknowledgments","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "EDI — Guided Tour",
            Slug = "edi-walkthrough",
            Summary = "A guided tour of the Admin > EDI page: sub-tabs, trading partner table, partner dialog, transaction list, filters, transaction detail, and retry.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Walkthrough,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 2,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","admin","walkthrough"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"appRoute":"/admin/edi","startButtonLabel":"Tour EDI","steps":[{"element":".edi-panel .tab-bar","popover":{"title":"The Two Tabs","description":"This page has two tabs. Trading Partners is where you set up the companies you swap documents with. Transactions shows every document that has come in or gone out. Click a tab to switch between them.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".edi-panel__toolbar .action-btn--create","popover":{"title":"Add a Trading Partner","description":"Click here to add a company you'll exchange documents with. You'll give it a name, pick the document format and how documents travel between you, and set whether they process automatically. You can also link the partner to a customer or vendor.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":"app-data-table[tableId='edi-partners']","popover":{"title":"Your Partners","description":"This table lists every partner you've set up. Each row shows the partner's name, its linked customer or vendor, the document format, how documents travel, how many documents you've exchanged, how many had errors, and whether it's active. Click a heading to sort.","side":"top"}},{"element":".edi-panel__actions","popover":{"title":"Buttons on Each Row","description":"Every partner row has four buttons: test the connection, open the part-number list that matches their part numbers to yours, edit the partner, and remove it. When you edit, the password box is left empty — leave it empty to keep the saved one, or type a new one to change it.","side":"left"}},{"element":".gap-note","popover":{"title":"Matching Their Parts to Yours","description":"This note points to the part-number list on each partner. It matches the part numbers a partner uses to your own, so incoming orders line up with your catalog automatically. Open it to add matches by hand or import a spreadsheet.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".tab:nth-child(2)","popover":{"title":"Transactions Tab","description":"Switch here to see every document exchanged. Each row shows the partner, whether it came in or went out, the document type, its status, what it created, when it arrived, and how many times it was retried.","side":"bottom"}}]}"""
        });

        // ── Field Reference (QuickRef) ───────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "EDI Field Reference",
            Slug = "edi-field-reference",
            Summary = "Complete reference for every field, status, format, transport method, button, and validation rule in the EDI module.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.QuickRef,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 3,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","admin","reference"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"title":"EDI Field Reference","groups":[{"heading":"Trading Partner Form Fields","items":[{"label":"Name (required)","value":"The name you'll recognize this partner by, such as 'Acme Corp EDI'. Up to 200 characters."},{"label":"Qualifier ID (required)","value":"A short code that says how the partner's ID is formatted. Common ones are '01' for a DUNS number, '08' for a UCC/EAN code, '12' for a phone number, and 'ZZ' when you and the partner simply agree on a code. Defaults to 'ZZ'."},{"label":"Qualifier Value (required)","value":"The partner's actual ID — the DUNS number, phone number, or agreed code that goes with the Qualifier ID above. Up to 100 characters."},{"label":"Default Format (required)","value":"The document format this partner uses. X12 is the North American standard; EDIFACT is the international one. Defaults to X12."},{"label":"Transport Method (required)","value":"How documents travel between you and the partner: AS2, SFTP, a VAN service, email, a direct connection, or manual upload. Defaults to Manual."},{"label":"Auto Process (on/off)","value":"When on (the default), incoming documents are read and applied automatically. When off, they wait at Received so you can review them first."},{"label":"Require Acknowledgment (on/off)","value":"When on (the default), the system automatically sends a receipt back to the partner confirming each document arrived. Defaults to on."},{"label":"Notes","value":"Optional free-form notes about the partner — contact info, special requirements, or anything worth remembering."}]},{"heading":"Trading Partner Table Columns","items":[{"label":"Name","value":"The partner's name. Click to sort."},{"label":"Customer","value":"The linked customer, or a dash if none is linked."},{"label":"Vendor","value":"The linked vendor, or a dash if none is linked."},{"label":"Format","value":"The document format: X12 or EDIFACT."},{"label":"Transport","value":"How documents travel: AS2, SFTP, a VAN, email, a direct connection, or manual."},{"label":"Txns","value":"How many documents you've exchanged with this partner in total."},{"label":"Errors","value":"How many documents ran into a problem. Shown as a red label when there are any."},{"label":"Active","value":"A green check when the partner is active, a gray mark when it isn't."},{"label":"Actions","value":"Four buttons: test the connection, open the part-number list, edit the partner, and remove it."}]},{"heading":"Transaction Table Columns","items":[{"label":"Partner","value":"The trading partner this document came from or went to."},{"label":"Dir","value":"Whether the document came in or went out. You can filter by this."},{"label":"Set","value":"The document type, shown as a number — for example an 850 (the customer's purchase order), an 810 (an invoice), or an 856 (a ship notice)."},{"label":"Control #","value":"The tracking number that identifies this document."},{"label":"Status","value":"A colored label showing where the document is in processing. You can filter by this."},{"label":"Entity","value":"What the document created in the system, such as a sales order or purchase order, or a dash if it hasn't been applied yet."},{"label":"Received","value":"The date and time the document arrived."},{"label":"Retries","value":"How many times a failed document has been retried."},{"label":"Actions","value":"A Retry button appears only on documents that ran into an error."}]},{"heading":"Transaction Detail Fields","items":[{"label":"Partner","value":"The trading partner this document is with."},{"label":"Direction","value":"Whether the document came in or went out."},{"label":"Transaction Set","value":"The document type, such as an 850 (a purchase order), an 810 (an invoice), or an 856 (a ship notice)."},{"label":"Status","value":"A colored label showing where the document is in processing."},{"label":"Error Message","value":"When a document fails, this red box explains what went wrong."},{"label":"Raw Payload","value":"The document exactly as it was received or sent, in its original format."},{"label":"Parsed Data","value":"The document after the system reads it, laid out as tidy fields — shown once it's been read successfully."}]},{"heading":"Transaction Statuses","items":[{"label":"Received (blue)","value":"The document arrived but hasn't been processed yet. This is where every incoming document starts, and where it waits if Auto Process is off."},{"label":"Parsing (yellow)","value":"The system is reading the document and pulling out its fields."},{"label":"Parsed","value":"The system finished reading the document successfully."},{"label":"Validating (yellow)","value":"The system is checking the document against your rules."},{"label":"Validated","value":"The checks passed. The document is ready to apply."},{"label":"Processing (yellow)","value":"The system is applying the document — creating or updating things like sales orders and purchase orders."},{"label":"Applied (green)","value":"Done. The document went through and the related record was created or updated. The Entity column shows what it made."},{"label":"Error (red)","value":"Processing failed somewhere. The error message explains why, and a Retry button appears."},{"label":"Acknowledged (gray)","value":"A receipt confirming this document arrived has been sent back to the partner."},{"label":"Rejected (red)","value":"The document was turned away during checking — the data didn't meet the rules, or the partner's part numbers couldn't be matched."}]},{"heading":"EDI Formats","items":[{"label":"X12","value":"The dominant standard in North America. Document types are numbered — for example 850 (purchase order), 810 (invoice), 856 (ship notice), and 855 (order acknowledgment)."},{"label":"EDIFACT","value":"The international standard, used widely in Europe and Asia. Document types have letter names like ORDERS (purchase order), INVOIC (invoice), and DESADV (ship notice)."}]},{"heading":"Transport Methods","items":[{"label":"AS2","value":"The most common business-to-business method. Documents are encrypted and signed, and the partner sends back a signed receipt confirming delivery."},{"label":"SFTP","value":"Secure file transfer. Documents are dropped into folders on a secure server that both sides share. Simple and reliable."},{"label":"VAN","value":"A go-between service (such as SPS Commerce or TrueCommerce) that routes documents between you and your partners and handles format differences for you."},{"label":"Email","value":"Documents sent as email attachments. Not very automated — usually for low-volume partners or as a backup."},{"label":"API","value":"A direct connection to the partner's system. A modern alternative to the traditional methods."},{"label":"Manual","value":"You upload and download documents yourself in the app. Best for testing, low-volume partners, or getting started before you automate."}]},{"heading":"SFTP Transport Fields (shown only when Transport = SFTP)","items":[{"label":"Host","value":"The address of the secure server where this partner exchanges files."},{"label":"Port","value":"The port to connect on. Defaults to 22."},{"label":"Username","value":"The login name for the server account."},{"label":"Password","value":"Type the password. It's stored securely and never shown again. When you come back to edit, this box is empty — leave it empty to keep the saved password, or type a new one to change it."},{"label":"Outbound Directory (we send)","value":"The folder on the server where outgoing documents are placed."},{"label":"Inbound Directory (we poll)","value":"The folder on the server checked for incoming documents."},{"label":"Password-kept-on-edit hint","value":"A note in the SFTP section: when a password is already saved it reads 'A password is stored. Leave blank to keep it; type a new one to replace it'; otherwise it reads 'The password is stored securely and never shown again.'"}]},{"heading":"Part-Number List","items":[{"label":"What it is","value":"A two-column list, one per partner, that matches the partner's part numbers to yours. Open it from the partner's row. You fill it in by typing — it's not a code editor."},{"label":"Partner Part #","value":"The part number the partner uses on their documents."},{"label":"Our Part #","value":"Your own part number that it matches to."},{"label":"Resolves To","value":"When your part number matches a real part in your catalog, its description shows here. If nothing matches, you'll see a 'No matching part' warning — the row still saves, but an order line using it comes in unmatched until that part exists."},{"label":"Add Row","value":"Adds a blank row so you can type a new pair."},{"label":"Import CSV","value":"Imports a two-column spreadsheet all at once. Re-importing an updated file refreshes existing rows instead of duplicating them. See the CSV Import reference."},{"label":"Save","value":"Saves the whole list and reloads it with fresh catalog matches."},{"label":"Delete row","value":"Removes that pair from the list. Takes effect when you save."}]},{"heading":"Buttons and Actions","items":[{"label":"New Trading Partner","value":"The main button on the Partners tab. Opens the form to add a partner."},{"label":"Test Connection","value":"On each partner row. Checks that the connection to the partner works and tells you whether it succeeded."},{"label":"Part-Number List","value":"On each partner row. Opens the list that matches the partner's part numbers to yours, where you can type entries or import a spreadsheet."},{"label":"Edit Partner","value":"On each partner row. Opens the partner form filled in with current values. The password box opens empty — leave it empty to keep the saved password, or type a new one to change it."},{"label":"Delete Partner","value":"On each partner row. Removes the partner."},{"label":"Retry Transaction","value":"On documents that ran into an error. Sends the document back through processing and confirms it's queued."},{"label":"View Transaction","value":"Click any document row to open its detail view — partner, direction, type, status, the original document, the read-out fields, and any errors."},{"label":"Close (transaction detail)","value":"Closes the document detail view."},{"label":"Save / Create (partner form)","value":"Saves the partner. It's turned off while the form is incomplete or saving. When it's off, a red warning triangle sits to its left — click it to see which fields still need attention."},{"label":"Cancel (partner form)","value":"Closes the form without saving."}]},{"heading":"Validation Rules","items":[{"label":"Name","value":"Required. Up to 200 characters."},{"label":"Qualifier ID","value":"Required. Up to 10 characters. Defaults to 'ZZ'."},{"label":"Qualifier Value","value":"Required. Up to 100 characters."},{"label":"Default Format","value":"Required. Must be X12 or EDIFACT."},{"label":"Transport Method","value":"Required. Must be one of AS2, SFTP, VAN, email, a direct connection, or manual."},{"label":"Submit button","value":"Turned off while the form is incomplete or saving. When it's off, a red warning triangle sits to its left — click it to see which fields need attention."}]},{"heading":"Transaction Filters","items":[{"label":"Direction filter","value":"Choose All (the default), incoming, or outgoing to narrow the list by which way the document went."},{"label":"Status filter","value":"Choose All (the default) or a single status — Received, Parsing, Parsed, Processing, Applied, Error, Acknowledged, or Rejected."},{"label":"Filter behavior","value":"Picking any filter updates the list right away."}]}]}"""
        });

        // ── Knowledge Check (Quiz) ───────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "EDI Knowledge Check",
            Slug = "edi-quiz",
            Summary = "Test your knowledge of the EDI module: formats, trading partners, transactions, mappings, statuses, and transport methods.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Quiz,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 4,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","admin","quiz"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"edi1","text":"A new customer requires EDI document exchange for purchase orders. Where do you set this up in QB Engineer?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to Customers, open the customer detail, and enable the EDI toggle"},{"id":"b","text":"Navigate to Admin > EDI, click New Trading Partner, and configure the partner with the customer's EDI identifiers, format, and transport method","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Create a new integration in Admin > Integrations and select EDI as the type"},{"id":"d","text":"Go to Admin > Settings and add the customer's EDI credentials to the system settings"}],"explanation":"Trading partners are managed under Admin > EDI. Click New Trading Partner and fill in the name, qualifier ID/value, default format (X12 or EDIFACT), transport method, and processing rules. You can link the partner to an existing Customer record."},{"id":"edi2","text":"What is the difference between X12 and EDIFACT?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"X12 is for invoices only, EDIFACT is for purchase orders only"},{"id":"b","text":"X12 is the North American standard using numeric transaction set codes (like 850, 810); EDIFACT is the international standard using alphabetic message types (like ORDERS, INVOIC)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"X12 is newer and replaces EDIFACT, which is deprecated"},{"id":"d","text":"X12 only works with AS2 transport, while EDIFACT only works with SFTP"}],"explanation":"X12 (ANSI ASC X12) is the dominant standard in North America, using 3-digit numeric codes for transaction sets (850=Purchase Order, 810=Invoice). EDIFACT (UN/EDIFACT) is the international standard using alphabetic codes (ORDERS, INVOIC). Both are actively used."},{"id":"edi3","text":"You see a transaction in the Transactions tab with status 'Error' (red chip). What action can you take?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Delete the transaction and ask the partner to resend"},{"id":"b","text":"Click the transaction row to view the error details, then click the Retry button to re-queue it for processing","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Change the status manually to Applied to force it through"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — error transactions are permanently failed and must be handled outside QB Engineer"}],"explanation":"Transactions in Error status show a Retry button (refresh icon) in the actions column. Click the row to see the error message and raw payload in the detail dialog, then click Retry to re-queue the transaction for processing. The retry count tracks how many attempts have been made."},{"id":"edi4","text":"What does the 'Auto Process' toggle on a trading partner control?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Whether outbound documents are sent automatically or queued for manual review"},{"id":"b","text":"Whether inbound documents are automatically parsed, validated, and applied, or held at Received status for manual review","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Whether the partner's connection is tested automatically every hour"},{"id":"d","text":"Whether duplicate documents from this partner are automatically rejected"}],"explanation":"When Auto Process is ON (default), inbound EDI documents are automatically processed through the full pipeline: Received → Parsing → Parsed → Validating → Validated → Processing → Applied. When OFF, documents stop at the Received status and require manual action to proceed."},{"id":"edi5","text":"A trading partner's Qualifier ID is set to 'ZZ'. What does this mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The partner uses a ZIP code as their identifier"},{"id":"b","text":"The identifier type is 'Mutually Defined' — the Qualifier Value is a code agreed upon by both parties","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The partner has not been fully configured yet and 'ZZ' is a placeholder"},{"id":"d","text":"The partner uses a DUNS number for identification"}],"explanation":"'ZZ' is the EDI qualifier code for 'Mutually Defined,' meaning both trading partners have agreed on the format and meaning of the Qualifier Value. It is the most common qualifier when partners don't use a standard identifier like DUNS ('01') or UCC/EAN ('08'). It is also the default in QB Engineer."},{"id":"edi6","text":"A customer sends EDI purchase orders using their own part numbers, not yours. How do you make inbound 850 lines match your catalog automatically?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Edit a JSON mapping file on the partner record that maps every EDI segment to a field"},{"id":"b","text":"Open that partner's Part-Number Map (the ⇄ action) and add rows — or import a CSV — pairing each partner part number with your part number","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Rename your catalog parts to match the customer's numbering scheme"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — EDI always matches on part description, so numbering doesn't matter"}],"explanation":"Each trading partner has a Part-Number Map, opened from the ⇄ (swap_horiz) action on the partner row. It is a typed two-column table (Partner Part # → Our Part #), built by hand or via CSV import — not a JSON editor. Inbound 850 lines translate through this map before matching your catalog; an unmapped line is still created but keeps the partner's number in the order-line notes for manual completion."},{"id":"edi7","text":"You want to see only inbound transactions that failed processing. How do you filter the transaction list?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Set the Direction filter to Inbound and the Status filter to Error","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Click the column header for Status and type 'Error' in the search box"},{"id":"c","text":"Use the search bar at the top and type 'Inbound Error'"},{"id":"d","text":"Switch to the Partners tab and look for partners with error counts > 0"}],"explanation":"The Transactions tab has two filter dropdowns at the top: Direction and Status. Set Direction to 'Inbound' and Status to 'Error' to see exactly the failed inbound transactions. The list refreshes immediately when you change either filter."},{"id":"edi8","text":"Which transport method provides built-in encryption, digital signatures, and delivery receipts (MDN)?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"SFTP"},{"id":"b","text":"Email"},{"id":"c","text":"AS2","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"VAN"}],"explanation":"AS2 (Applicability Statement 2) is the most common B2B EDI protocol. It uses HTTP/HTTPS with S/MIME encryption, digital signatures for authentication, and Message Disposition Notifications (MDN) to confirm delivery. It is the preferred transport for high-volume, security-sensitive EDI exchanges."},{"id":"edi9","text":"A trading partner has 'Require Acknowledgment' enabled. What happens when you receive an inbound document from them?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"QB Engineer sends a functional acknowledgment (997 for X12 or CONTRL for EDIFACT) back to the partner confirming receipt and processing status","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"QB Engineer sends an email notification to the admin user that a document was received"},{"id":"c","text":"The transaction is held until a user manually clicks an Acknowledge button"},{"id":"d","text":"The partner's system automatically marks the document as delivered without any action from QB Engineer"}],"explanation":"When Require Acknowledgment is ON, QB Engineer automatically sends a functional acknowledgment — a 997 transaction set for X12 or a CONTRL message for EDIFACT — back to the trading partner. The acknowledgment transaction is linked to the original inbound transaction for traceability."},{"id":"edi10","text":"What does the 'Test Connection' button (wifi icon) do on a trading partner row?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Sends a test EDI document to the partner to verify end-to-end processing"},{"id":"b","text":"Sends a connectivity test to the partner's configured transport endpoint and reports success or failure via a snackbar message","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Pings the partner's IP address to check if their server is online"},{"id":"d","text":"Toggles the partner between test mode and production mode"}],"explanation":"The Test Connection button sends a connectivity test to the partner's transport endpoint (AS2 URL, SFTP server, VAN mailbox, etc.). It shows a success snackbar if the connection succeeds or an error snackbar with the failure message if it doesn't. It does not send any actual EDI documents."},{"id":"edi11","text":"An EDI transaction shows a status of 'Acknowledged' (gray chip). What does this mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The transaction was received but is waiting for a user to acknowledge and begin processing"},{"id":"b","text":"A functional acknowledgment (997/CONTRL) has been sent for this inbound transaction, confirming receipt to the trading partner","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The related entity (e.g., Sales Order) has been acknowledged by the warehouse team"},{"id":"d","text":"The transaction failed but was acknowledged as a known issue that will not be retried"}],"explanation":"The Acknowledged status means a functional acknowledgment (997 for X12 or CONTRL for EDIFACT) was sent to the trading partner confirming that the inbound document was received and processed. The acknowledgment transaction is linked to the original for full traceability."},{"id":"edi12","text":"You need to set up EDI for a low-volume vendor who sends purchase orders occasionally. You are still configuring the integration. Which transport method is most appropriate to start with?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"AS2 — it is the industry standard and should be used from day one"},{"id":"b","text":"Manual — upload and download documents through the QB Engineer UI while you configure and test the full integration","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"VAN — always use a VAN for low-volume partners to reduce complexity"},{"id":"d","text":"API — set up a direct REST API connection for maximum speed"}],"explanation":"Manual transport lets you upload and download EDI documents directly through the QB Engineer UI. It is the best choice for initial setup, testing, and low-volume partners because it requires no external infrastructure. You can switch to AS2, SFTP, or a VAN later once the integration is validated."}]}"""
