        // ── EDI — Advanced Reference (Reference) ─────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "EDI — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "edi-reference",
            Summary = "Edge-case and power-user reference for EDI: qualifier ID codes, partner→Customer/Vendor linking, control numbers, transport deep dive, and why UOM/pack-qty translation isn't built.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## EDI — Advanced Reference\n\nDeeper and edge-case notes for the EDI page (Admin > EDI). This is reference material, not a tutorial — see the core EDI modules for the day-to-day workflow.\n\n## Qualifier ID Codes\n\nThe **Qualifier ID** on a trading partner is a short code (up to 10 characters) that tells the other side how to read the partner's **Qualifier Value**. It isn't the partner's identity; it's the *type* of identity. Together, the Qualifier ID and Qualifier Value uniquely identify the partner on every document.\n\nCommon values:\n\n- **01** — DUNS (a Dun & Bradstreet 9-digit number).\n- **08** — UCC/EAN (GS1) location number.\n- **12** — a phone number used as the identifier.\n- **14** — DUNS+4 (a DUNS number plus a 4-digit suffix for a sub-location).\n- **ZZ** — Mutually Defined. You and the partner simply agree on what the value means. This is the default because most small and mid-size relationships negotiate a code rather than use a registered one.\n\nLess common but valid codes you may see in a partner's spec: **02** (SCAC), **04** (IATA), **09** (X.121), **20** (HIN), **30** (US Federal Tax ID / EIN). Note that **AS2** is a way of sending documents, not a qualifier — don't confuse the two. Enter whatever code the partner's setup guide calls for; the system stores it exactly as you type it and doesn't check it against any registry.\n\n## Linking a Partner to a Customer or Vendor\n\nA trading partner is an EDI address; a customer or vendor is a business record. Linking the two lets the system route an incoming document to the right account automatically.\n\n- A partner can be linked to a customer (the usual case for incoming purchase orders), to a vendor (for documents you receive as a buyer), to both, or to neither.\n- The link drives account matching during processing: when an incoming 850 (a customer's purchase order) is applied, the resulting sales order is created against the linked customer. With no link, the document still reads fine but has no account to attach to, so it waits for someone to sort it out by hand.\n- The link is separate from the routing IDs the partner uses to address documents. Those routing IDs point at the partner's mailbox; the customer or vendor link points at the account.\n- One business can hold both a customer link and a vendor link on the same partner if you sell to and buy from them under one EDI relationship.\n\n## Control Numbers\n\nEvery document tracks three nested tracking numbers, from the widest to the narrowest, and shows them in the document detail view.\n\n- **Control #** (the interchange number) — identifies the whole batch exchanged between two partners. This is the value shown as 'Control #' in the transactions list.\n- **Group number** — identifies a group of like documents inside that batch.\n- **Transaction number** — identifies the single document inside the group.\n\nAny of the three can be empty — a partner that skips a level, or a document you uploaded by hand, may not fill in every one. Receipts you send back reference these numbers so the partner knows exactly which batch, group, or document you're confirming or turning down.\n\n## More on Transport (AS2, VAN, API)\n\nThe six ways to move documents are AS2, SFTP, a VAN service, email, a direct connection, and manual upload. Beyond the one-line summaries in the core reference, here's what actually sets them apart:\n\n- **AS2** — A direct, encrypted connection between you and the partner. Its defining feature is the signed receipt the partner returns, which proves the document was delivered. No middleman; you set up credentials directly with the partner. Best for direct, high-volume relationships.\n- **VAN** (Value Added Network) — A go-between mailbox service (SPS Commerce, TrueCommerce, Cleo, and so on) that sits between you and the partner. The VAN handles delivery, often smooths over format differences, and connects to other VANs. You connect once and reach many partners. It trades a per-document cost for no direct setup.\n- **API** — A direct connection to the partner's system, skipping the traditional EDI methods entirely. Large retailers and marketplaces increasingly offer this. The content may still be X12 or EDIFACT, or the partner's own format that the system reads the same way.\n- **SFTP** — Dropping files into shared folders on a secure server. Outgoing documents go in one folder; incoming ones are picked up from another. It has its own settings (server address, port, login, password, and the two folders).\n- **Email** and **Manual** — low-automation fallbacks. Manual is the recommended starting point while you test a new partner before switching to an automated method.\n\nSwitching a partner's transport is just picking a different option and supplying the new credentials — it doesn't change the partner's identity, its links, or its document history.\n\n## Unit and Pack-Quantity Translation (Not Built)\n\nThe part-number list matches a partner's part number to yours — a pure number swap. It deliberately does **not** convert units of measure or pack quantities.\n\n- If a partner orders in cases and you stock in single units, or the partner's order line uses a unit (each, case, box, pallet) different from how you stock the part, the system does **not** convert the quantity. The number flows through as-is against your part.\n- There is no unit cross-reference and no pack-quantity multiplier in EDI today. Treat any partner that needs this as a setup conversation, not a self-service step.\n- Practical guardrail: for partners whose ordering unit differs from your stocking unit, review applied orders before fulfilling them, or agree with the partner to order in your stocking unit. This is the most common source of quantity surprises on incoming orders, and it's called out here precisely because the screen gives you no control for it.\n","sections":[]}"""
        });

